WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:14.000
Ladies and gentlemen, friends of Tennessee, this is not a very pleasant matter to talk

00:14.000 --> 00:16.000
about, but it's a very important one.

00:16.000 --> 00:20.680
And I think it's one that people ought to have information about.

00:20.680 --> 00:26.600
That is, in the case of a nuclear attack or an old-out war, what will happen to our civilian

00:26.600 --> 00:28.320
population?

00:28.320 --> 00:32.040
What kind of civilian defense do we have?

00:32.040 --> 00:37.160
Back about 10 or 12 years ago, as chairman of a subcommittee of the Armed Services Committee

00:37.160 --> 00:43.040
in the Senate, I guided through the first Civil Defense Act.

00:43.040 --> 00:47.400
Since that time, we have seen many developments and a good deal has been done in the Civil

00:47.400 --> 00:49.560
Defense way.

00:49.560 --> 00:55.520
And I think that people, while they may not be interested, they don't like to think about

00:55.520 --> 00:57.920
civil defense particularly.

00:57.920 --> 01:02.920
This is a problem that they should have the most accurate and up-to-date information

01:02.920 --> 01:09.200
concerning because we never know what may unfortunately happen.

01:09.200 --> 01:14.080
Today we have is our guest, Stuart L. Pittman, who is the Assistant Secretary of Defense

01:14.080 --> 01:16.200
for Civil Defense.

01:16.200 --> 01:23.160
And he is running the show at the federal level, coordinating or attempting to coordinate

01:23.160 --> 01:26.160
the activities throughout the country.

01:26.160 --> 01:33.080
And we appreciate having you here, Secretary Pittman, to talk with the listeners and viewers

01:33.080 --> 01:37.120
of this station about the all-important matter of civil defense.

01:37.120 --> 01:39.120
Delighted to be here, Senator.

01:39.120 --> 01:47.000
Now, in the first place, of course, you are a Assistant Secretary of Defense.

01:47.000 --> 01:49.400
But is this a federal problem entirely?

01:49.400 --> 01:55.480
Or is it not, if we are going to be successful, I like the local aspects of it?

01:55.480 --> 02:01.600
Well, on the way, we picture a nuclear attack in the years ahead of heavy nuclear attack.

02:01.600 --> 02:06.440
It seems quite clear that each community has to be prepared to stand on its own feet

02:06.440 --> 02:10.240
for a matter of perhaps weeks, and they cannot be sure about side-help.

02:10.240 --> 02:13.160
So it's clearly a local problem.

02:13.160 --> 02:17.160
And then, of course, the federal government does play a role in trying to coordinate the

02:17.160 --> 02:22.640
effort and help where you can, but it is a largely a local problem.

02:22.640 --> 02:26.320
If it should ever happen, it would be very much a local problem, but in the preparations

02:26.320 --> 02:30.720
the federal government must support state and local efforts very heavily.

02:30.720 --> 02:36.880
Well, Stewart, how much has the President asked for this year for civil defense and

02:36.880 --> 02:37.880
the budget?

02:37.880 --> 02:42.760
Well, our request for fiscal year 1964 is 300 million.

02:42.760 --> 02:49.640
It's less than was asked for last year, but a video more than we got last year.

02:49.640 --> 02:53.480
How much did you get last year, and how much was spent on civil defense last year?

02:53.480 --> 03:02.560
Last year, our appropriation was 113 million, and we are requesting a supplemental, which

03:02.560 --> 03:07.360
would increase that to 175 million for this current fiscal year.

03:07.360 --> 03:14.360
Well, civil defense is an overall part of our defense program, is it not?

03:14.360 --> 03:17.040
It's very much so.

03:17.040 --> 03:22.080
And our overall defense program, I think, the budget this year is something like a 60-year

03:22.080 --> 03:27.040
request for appropriation is something like 60 billion dollars.

03:27.040 --> 03:28.040
It's 52.

03:28.040 --> 03:33.120
It turns out to be 6 tenths of 1 percent of the total defense budget that we are requesting

03:33.120 --> 03:34.120
for civil defense.

03:34.120 --> 03:35.120
I see.

03:35.120 --> 03:40.720
Well, one second here, and McNamara requested in the way of civil defense legislation.

03:40.720 --> 03:47.360
He's requesting legislation, which would permit us to start on the second leg of this

03:47.360 --> 03:48.360
program.

03:48.360 --> 03:52.480
We found a shellerspace for over 100 million people.

03:52.480 --> 03:54.480
It already exists.

03:54.480 --> 03:58.160
No money need be spent on the structure.

03:58.160 --> 04:04.400
It simply has to be stock now, that's not enough to take care of the population with

04:04.400 --> 04:06.800
minimal shellers protection.

04:06.800 --> 04:13.400
We need it far too to put some money into selected buildings in communities to create additional

04:13.400 --> 04:17.200
shellerspace, which would protect people against fallout radiation.

04:17.200 --> 04:22.440
You mean, at present time you found some kind of shellerspace for about 100 million of

04:22.440 --> 04:24.880
our 180 million population.

04:24.880 --> 04:26.480
Is that right?

04:26.480 --> 04:31.520
But how about supplies, medicine, food, water, things of that sort?

04:31.520 --> 04:38.280
As you have mentioned in an including radiation detection instruments, it's going into each

04:38.280 --> 04:43.200
of the shellers that have been found to be acceptable in this survey, which we have just

04:43.200 --> 04:47.160
completed, and they would also go into the new shellerspace created by the program we're

04:47.160 --> 04:48.160
asking for.

04:48.160 --> 04:52.800
Well, there's been a argument that's been raging for some time about the best way to save

04:52.800 --> 04:57.240
lives in case of nuclear attack.

04:57.240 --> 05:02.000
Some have said that shellers in our big cities offer the best opportunity of being protected

05:02.000 --> 05:05.160
against fallout.

05:05.160 --> 05:10.120
Others have argued that we ought to evacuate our cities in the event of a warning of a

05:10.120 --> 05:14.840
nuclear attack, get out in the country and the countryside.

05:14.840 --> 05:16.320
What has been resolved about that?

05:16.320 --> 05:18.160
What should people do?

05:18.160 --> 05:24.200
Well, the one big change in civil defense planning over the last few years has been a shift

05:24.200 --> 05:31.440
away from the idea of evacuation towards a take cover approach to the problem.

05:31.440 --> 05:37.960
This is largely because of the fallout radiation hazard we anticipate that under a heavy nuclear

05:37.960 --> 05:43.080
attack it would reach most of the country so there would be no place to run to.

05:43.080 --> 05:47.920
Unless you had a sheller at the end of your journey, you'd better stay where you are and

05:47.920 --> 05:55.360
take advantage of the massive building materials that are near where you live if you live

05:55.360 --> 05:56.360
in a city.

05:56.360 --> 05:59.200
Certainly it would be better to take advantage of that protection than to run out into

05:59.200 --> 06:01.760
the country where you'd be exposed to fallout radiation.

06:01.760 --> 06:06.760
I mean, you're just the exposed value where running out and then you'd have to have somewhere

06:06.760 --> 06:11.600
to go to then after you evacuate it.

06:11.600 --> 06:21.000
Well, aside from the war threat during the Cuban crisis, it doesn't seem to me that there's

06:21.000 --> 06:26.120
been very much and certainly not sufficient interest in civil defense.

06:26.120 --> 06:30.080
Is that right and what should be done about it?

06:30.080 --> 06:32.800
Well, I think that is generally right, Senator.

06:32.800 --> 06:39.760
The Cuban experience, however, did demonstrate clearly to the leadership in this country.

06:39.760 --> 06:44.920
I mean, local public and private leadership, not just the federal government, that people

06:44.920 --> 06:51.840
faced with a real crisis are deeply concerned about their chances of survival and a place

06:51.840 --> 06:55.960
to go to take their families that would give them some protection so that I don't think

06:55.960 --> 06:59.760
there's as much speculation as there was about whether people really want this.

06:59.760 --> 07:03.600
I think it's clear that an emergency they want it.

07:03.600 --> 07:08.480
It's also clear that between emergencies they're not going to think about it deeply and

07:08.480 --> 07:11.400
involve themselves emotionally in the problem.

07:11.400 --> 07:12.680
I think this is all right.

07:12.680 --> 07:21.320
I think it's up to the leadership to do the planning and the general public has a responsibility

07:21.320 --> 07:29.920
to understand the problem, but need not do extravagant and extraordinary things day-to-day

07:29.920 --> 07:30.920
basis.

07:30.920 --> 07:31.920
That's not necessary.

07:31.920 --> 07:39.720
Well, Secretary Pitman, if you were living in a suburb of the city, or if you're living

07:39.720 --> 07:45.160
in a small town, a nuclear attack came, what should people do?

07:45.160 --> 07:50.560
What would you recommend that they do?

07:50.560 --> 07:59.560
Well, of course, anything you can do at the last minute is negligible compared to what

07:59.560 --> 08:04.200
you could do if you faced the problem a little ahead of time.

08:04.200 --> 08:13.560
Every family in the suburb or anywhere else should have some idea of the best protection

08:13.560 --> 08:17.600
against a four-out radiation, which is the most predictable of the hazards that would

08:17.600 --> 08:18.960
take place.

08:18.960 --> 08:23.160
That means a pick out of place which might be a basement in your home, it might be a large

08:23.160 --> 08:25.760
building nearby.

08:25.760 --> 08:30.480
If you don't have any place that offers any kind of protection, consideration should

08:30.480 --> 08:36.480
be given to a home shelter, and we have designs that have been published to show how this

08:36.480 --> 08:42.160
can be done at very low cost or $150 if you do a little work yourself with a shelter

08:42.160 --> 08:46.000
in your basement or backyard.

08:46.000 --> 08:49.160
This kind of preparation is taken.

08:49.160 --> 08:53.160
Then you can build a family plan, a community plan that makes some sense.

08:53.160 --> 08:55.520
These things haven't been done.

08:55.520 --> 08:59.680
It's a very difficult thing to advise people what to do during an emergency.

08:59.680 --> 09:07.040
Of course, the best thing to do is to try to get acquainted with the location of the facilities

09:07.040 --> 09:13.600
of some good shelter or well-provisioned that's already been built that you could get to.

09:13.600 --> 09:21.440
In Nashville, for example, in your state, we have found Shellerspace to take care of

09:21.440 --> 09:23.240
the entire population.

09:23.240 --> 09:26.560
In Memphis, there's enough to take care of about half the population.

09:26.560 --> 09:29.760
So it varies from city to city.

09:29.760 --> 09:30.760
This is not evident.

09:30.760 --> 09:33.000
It hasn't come to the surface.

09:33.000 --> 09:38.240
It hasn't all been marked so that people don't see this, but this is a reality in over

09:38.240 --> 09:40.040
this coming year.

09:40.040 --> 09:44.640
It will be stocked in marks and there will be plans as to how people will use it.

09:44.640 --> 09:49.080
People will know living in various sections of Nashville where they are supposed to go

09:49.080 --> 09:55.080
and what the shelter is available to them.

09:55.080 --> 09:59.960
Yes, you have a very able state director and criminal fox who is working on plans to

09:59.960 --> 10:00.960
strut people.

10:00.960 --> 10:01.960
Yes, I know.

10:01.960 --> 10:06.200
He's got a lot of very able directors in our various cities and towns.

10:06.200 --> 10:13.280
When I take out state of Tennessee by the population of three million, 600,000 as an example, what

10:13.280 --> 10:16.880
facts have your studies revealed about civil events?

10:16.880 --> 10:18.720
How many shelter facilities are there?

10:18.720 --> 10:21.880
The number of spaces and what's the supply?

10:21.880 --> 10:27.680
The status of the supply of food and water and other things that people must have.

10:27.680 --> 10:32.680
The number of spaces that we've found in this nationwide survey in Tennessee are about

10:32.680 --> 10:36.800
one point space to take care of, about 1.6 million people.

10:36.800 --> 10:40.880
That's about 45% of the state population.

10:40.880 --> 10:45.600
The survey has also revealed that simply by adding ventilation and basements, it's been

10:45.600 --> 10:52.920
increased the capacity of the shelter space in these larger buildings to about 2.4 million

10:52.920 --> 10:57.800
people, which means that about 70% of the population could be taken care of.

10:57.800 --> 10:59.520
That's a 50% increase.

10:59.520 --> 11:01.320
This costs some money.

11:01.320 --> 11:05.600
The national average costs and the ventilation is around $11 per person.

11:05.600 --> 11:12.400
Sheldart, those institutions that are eligible under this proposed financing program that

11:12.400 --> 11:17.640
I mentioned earlier, which we're presenting to Congress, could have federal funds which

11:17.640 --> 11:19.600
would meet this cost.

11:19.600 --> 11:24.000
These include all nonprofit institution schools and hospitals and public buildings.

11:24.000 --> 11:27.440
It does not include industrial commercial establishments.

11:27.440 --> 11:31.840
What part is the TVA played in civil defense planning?

11:31.840 --> 11:40.520
The TVA has taken a very active interest in this and done what all federal agencies should

11:40.520 --> 11:44.000
be doing, which is to demonstrate some leadership.

11:44.000 --> 11:51.880
They have gone ahead and marked and equipped their buildings, which offer some possibility

11:51.880 --> 11:53.480
of community shelter space.

11:53.480 --> 12:00.840
They've also taken measures to assure continuity of the power system and so far as this can

12:00.840 --> 12:02.840
be done.

12:02.840 --> 12:09.840
In their own buildings or installations do they have civil defense, do they have

12:09.840 --> 12:10.840
shoulders?

12:10.840 --> 12:11.840
Yes.

12:11.840 --> 12:16.840
They have identified the buildings and moving in supplies and developing plans to use them.

12:16.840 --> 12:22.200
I suppose having a power facility in the event of a attack is very important too.

12:22.200 --> 12:23.200
It's of course vital.

12:23.200 --> 12:28.280
It's a very difficult subject as to how to switch power around from one station to another

12:28.280 --> 12:31.360
to restore services rapidly as possible.

12:31.360 --> 12:33.120
We're doing a lot of research on this.

12:33.120 --> 12:36.560
We're optimistic that a good part of the country would have power.

12:36.560 --> 12:40.200
Of course there would be important parts of the country that would be without power.

12:40.200 --> 12:46.400
Well, Stuart briefly, because you give us an example of a program supporting civil defense,

